<H3> <TI>   Ministers Discuss Arms Industry Transformation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ministers Discuss Arms Industry Transformation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU3103141394 Prague CTK in English 1133 GMT 31 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU3103141394 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, March 31 (CTK) -- Relevant ministers, who 
met to discuss the Czech arms industry and its transformation, 
have decided to divide long-term defense contracts into two 
groups according to their importance to the state, Premier 
Vaclav Klaus said today. 
  Within six months, the Ministry of Defense will work out a 
proposal describing its expected contracts with Czech arms 
producers. One group of items will contain those with direct 
effect on the country's security interests. The other defined 
group will involve less government attention, Klaus said. 
  He noted that the state does not plan to organize arms 
exports. It will simply ensure that competition in the arms 
industry is not lessened, and that no laws are broken. 
  Defense Minister Antonin Baudys said before the ministers' 
meeting that Czech companies will be allowed to participate in 
the country's arms conversion process according to their 
abilities. Discussions with them will start once the ministry 
has drawn up its proposal. 
  Arms conversion in the Czech Republic could be carried out 
over five to ten years, Baudys noted. 
  Most important, said Deputy Foreign Minister Alexandr 
Vondra, 
is for the Czech armed forces to state their modernization needs 
and for the state to be ready to cooperate with arms producers. 
  The issue of re-equipping is not the only path to 
compatibility with NATO, he added. 

</TEXT>

