<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Criticizes Trade Concessions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Opposition Criticizes Trade Concessions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0104073394 Prague CTK in English 2001 GMT 31 Mar 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0104073394 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, March 31 (CTK) -- Representatives of 
the "shadow cabinet" of former Slovak Premier Vladimir Meciar 
today criticized what they said was a retreat by the new Slovak 
Government from its protectionist policy towards Czech exports. 
  "I'm surprised at Slovakia's unlimited cooperative approach 
towards colleagues from the Czech Republic, because a 
cooperative approach in trade relations ought to be mutual," 
former Economics Minister Jan Ducky told a press conference. He 
was referring to the recent Czech-Slovak preliminary agreement 
on the mutual recognition of certificates for food products and 
consumer goods. 
  Ducky criticized the amended Czech law on value-added tax, 
saying that the new calculation of the tax on goods imported 
from the Czech Republic would have a more severe effect on 
Slovak exports than the Slovak-imposed import surcharge had on 
imports from the Czech Republic. 
  Ducky also said that Slovak food exports to the Czech 
Republic were only a fraction of Czech exports to Slovakia and 
that the mutual recognition of certificates would harm Slovakia. 
  Former Vice-Premier Sergej Kozlik said the Meciar government 
had succeeded in reducing the deficit on the new clearing 
account for trade with the Czech Republic from 127 million ECU 
[European Currency Unit] to the present 19 million. Kozlik said 
that while Slovakia's deficit on the old account (for payments 
before the currency separation on February 8, 1993) amounted to 
470 million crowns at the end of February, now it was two 
billion crowns. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

