<H3> <TI>   Prime Minister Urges Continued Privatization </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Prime Minister Urges Continued Privatization </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2903192294 Budapest MTI in English 1742 GMT 29 Mar 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2903192294 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 29 March (MTI) -- "If we want Hungary to 
become a western-type democracy, we have to continue 
privatization, namely the transformation of state assets into 
human ones," Hungarian Prime Minister Peter Boross said in a 
speech, closing a two-day conference on privatization held in 
Budapest by the Central and East European Christian Democratic 
Academy. 
  Addressing an audience of foreign experts and advisers, 
Boross spoke in detail about the historical heritage and 
environment that determine privatization in Hungary. 
  Change in ownership always provides opportunities for 
corruption, Boross said, admitting that there had been some 
serious abuses of privatization in Hungary, too. He warned, 
however, that it would be a mistake to draw general conclusions 
from these cases. 
  The prime minister spoke in favor of consistent pursuit of 
privatization and concluded his address saying, "private 
ownership will soon prevail in Hungary's economy." 

</TEXT>

