<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jovanovic: FRY Not Alone Despite Sanctions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Jovanovic: FRY Not Alone Despite Sanctions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0304125694 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1221 GMT 3 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0304125694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, April 3 (TANJUG) -- Yugoslav Foreign 
Minister Vladislav Jovanovic said on Sunday that he received new 
encouragement in Belarus that Yugoslavia is not alone despite 
its isolation and the international sanctions, and that the 
circle of countries which are showing solidarity with its 
justified objectives and resistance to outside pressure, 
sanctions and isolation, is spreading. 
  "The talks we had in Minsk covered all the aspects of the 
Yugoslav crisis, primarily the crisis in Bosnia-Herzegovina," 
Jovanovic told Radio Belgrade upon his return from the first 
official visit to Belarus since it became independent. 
  "Both sides underscored identical interests that the crisis 
in the space of former Yugoslavia end as soon as possible, that 
Yugoslavia recover its legitimate rights in international 
relations," Jovanovic set out. 
  Speaking About the talks in Moscow, which he visited 
earlier, 
Jovanovic said that he had agreed with Russian Foreign Minister 
Andrey Kozyrev that developments in Bosnia-Herzegovina were 
marked by positive changes, but that there were still serious 
situations which made it imperative for both countries to be 
very active and to collaborate even more closely. 
  It was underscored that Russia had played an important 
positive role in the resolving of recent crisis situations, but 
that it can have an even more active role in removing the 
obstacles to peace, of which the biggest is the continued 
maintenance of the sanctions against Yugoslavia, Jovanovic said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

