<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Issues Statement on Ethnic Cleansing </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Issues Statement on Ethnic Cleansing </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0404144694 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1300 GMT 4 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0404144694 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Reviewing the grave situation in the republic which 
resulted from the continued aggression and ethnic cleansing on 
the occupied territories of the republic, our country's 
government, at today's session -- Prime Minister Haris Silajdzic 
presided -- adopted the following statement: 
  Two years have passed since the aggression on the sovereign 
and internationally recognized Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
The consequences of this aggression are over 200,000 killed and 
some 1,250,000 refugees and displaced persons. Unfortunately, 
the Serbian occupying forces are continuing the process of 
ethnic cleansing with relentless intensity, particularly in the 
areas of Banja Luka, Prijedor, Stipovo, Jajce, and other parts 
of the Bosnian Krajina. 
  The international public is acquainted with the dramatic 
news 
of murders and other forms of pressure against the non-Serbian 
population and with preparations for the evacuation of the 
remaining non-Serbian population. The government uses this 
occasion to lodge an energetic protest because of the fact that 
the international community is not showing a readiness to stop 
the aggressor in this fascist endeavor. 
  We call on the United Nations, the European Union, and the 
United States to do everything in their power to prevent the 
conclusion of the process of ethnic cleansing and that all 
citizens are granted the elementary conditions for safety of 
property and personal safety, and are guaranteed all other human 
liberties and rights established by international treaties and 
the Bosnia-Herzegovina Constitution. We call on all states, 
signatories of the Convention on the Prevention and Punishment 
of the Crime of Genocide from 1949 to carry out immediately all 
the obligations pursuant to this convention. 
  The Bosnia-Herzegovina Government believes that the 
international community has failed to react to the 
Serbo-Montenegrin aggressor's attacks at Gorazde and Bihac. 
Since these attacks are attacks on protected areas as 
stipulated by UN Resolution 824, the Bosnia-Herzegovina 
Government has taken measures with the goal of activating the 
mechanisms of the UN Security Council in order to stop these 
attacks and protect the civilian population. The government 
maintains the position that the aggressor is calling into 
question the continuation of peace negotiations and that the 
international community is obliged to take all measures to stop 
the attacks and create conditions for the continuation of the 
peace process. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-7600 </DOCNO>
