<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UNHCR on `Campaign of Terror' Against Muslims </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UNHCR on `Campaign of Terror' Against Muslims </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0104155994 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1300 GMT 1 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0104155994 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kris Janovski, spokesman for the UN High 
Commissioner for Refugees [UNHCR] in Sarajevo, presented today, 
as he put it: Alarming news from Banja Luka on the 
intensification of the campaign of terror against the Bosniak 
people in that part of Bosnia. Over the last few days in 
Prijedor at least 7 Bosniak civilians were killed in retaliation 
for casualties the aggressor's army suffered in central Bosnia. 
The civilians were murdered after bodies of six of the 
aggressor's policemen, killed in the fighting around Doboj, were 
returned to Prijedor. All the Bosniaks have had their telephones 
cut off. The UNHCR was first informed of this terrible crime by 
a Muslim woman hiding in the house of her Serb neighbor. 
  [Word indistinct] is continuing in Sanski Most, where Serb 
refugees are moved into the homes of Bosniaks, Kris Janovski 
said. Exposed to constant pressure and unbearable living 
conditions, the Bosniaks are simply forced to leave their homes. 
Some 850 Serbs, refugees from Zenica, Zepce, and Zavidovici 
have recently arrived in Banja Luka, and they are accommodated 
through the expulsion of Bosniaks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-7604 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu064_i_94011" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-064 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  3 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karadzic Assails Efforts To `Create Chaos' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Karadzic Assails Efforts To `Create Chaos' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0304172894 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1718 GMT 3 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0304172894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, April 3 (TANJUG) -- President of the 
Bosnian Serb republic (R.S.) Radovan Karadzic on Sunday ordered 
legal proceedings against and severe punishment of persons who 
have been trying to create chaos and discredit the civilian 
authorities of the Serb state. 
  Karadzic gave strict orders for the investigation in 
Prijedor, a town in the western R.S., to be stepped up and all 
persons responsible for the latest developments in that town to 
be arrested, a statement released by the presidential office 
said. 
  Karadzic stressed that the enemies of the R.S. were 
intensifying attacks on the republic's independence and 
sovereignty in an effort to create chaos, discredit the civilian 
authorities of the R.S., and thwart the functioning of the Serb 
state, the statement, a copy of which has been sent to TANJUG, 
said. 
  The R.S. president gave strict orders to all civilian and 
military authorities to offer all necessary assistance to the 
International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC). 
  All perpetrators of the crimes will be tried and most 
severely punished before the eyes of the international public, 
Karadzic said. 
  R.S. Prime Minister Vladimir Lukic on Saturday sharply 
protested because of an UNHCR report on an alleged deterioration 
of the position of Muslims and Croats in the region of the 
Bosnian Serb town of Banja Luka. 
  UNHCR officials uncritically drew up the report solely on 
the 
basis of statements by the local bishop and mufti and 
representatives of the Catholic humanitarian organization 
Caritas, and failed even to mention the criminal charges brought 
against individuals engaged in criminal activities of damaging 
the property of Muslims and Croats in the Banja Luka region, 
Lukic said in a letter sent to the Zagreb-based UNHCR 
representative. 
  The UNHCR report, which accused the R.S. authorities of 
allegedly not respecting the rights of the minority Muslim and 
Croat populations, was aimed at discrediting the R.S. 
authorities and attracting the attention of the international 
community and media, the R.S. prime minister said in the letter. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-7605 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu064_i_94012" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-064 </AU>
