<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Muslims Step Up Attacks on Serbs Around Doboj </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Muslims Step Up Attacks on Serbs Around Doboj </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0304213994 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2129 GMT 3 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0304213994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Banja Luka, April 3 (TANJUG) -- The Bosnian Moslem 
army has stepped up attacks on Serb defence lines in the area of 
Doboj in the north of the former Yugoslav republic of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina while their attacks in the areas of Gorazde, 
Cajnice and Foca in eastern Bosnia are becoming less intensive 
after a defeat of their troops in the area. 
  Bosnian Serb army sources said on Sunday evening that the 
strongest Moslem assaults had been reported in the area of Mount 
Ozren, south of Doboj, where they had carried out several 
infantry attacks on Sunday morning before being forced to 
retreat with major casualties in their ranks. 
  The Moslems fired ten shells on Doboj and continued to bring 
in fresh troops to the Teslic battlefront in the south. 
  As part of an all-out offensive on the territory of the 
Bosnian Serb republic, Moslems have been continually shelling 
Doboj over the past five days, causing great damage to the town. 
  Moslem units continued attacks in the area of Trebava east 
of 
Doboj and in the area of Brcko north of that town, as well as in 
the region of Srbobran (formerly Donji Vakuf) and Mt. Vlasic in 
central Bosnia. 
  Despite a defeat suffered over the past few days in the 
areas 
of Gorazde, Cajnice and Foca, the Moslem army is carrying out 
new mobilization and re-grouping of its troops, Bosnian Serb 
army sources said. 
  They said they had received an information that the Moslems 
had on Saturday night expected in vain a large quantity of 
weapons, ammunition and food to be airdropped in the Gorazde 
area. 
  The Bosnian Serb army command said on Saturday that it 
possessed proofs that the airdrop operation (in which 
humanitarian supplies are parachuted to the population of Moslem 
enclaves in eastern Bosnia, including Gorazde) was being used 
for supplying the Moslem army with up-to-date arms. 
  The Bosnian Moslem army has used those weapons in its latest 
offensive on Serb positions from the direction of Gorazde, where 
more than 10,000 Moslem fighters are based in spite of the fact 
that the enclave should have been demilitarized a long time ago 
under a resolution of the United Nations which proclaimed the 
town a "safe area." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-7611 </DOCNO>
