<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jarcevic Welcomes Extension for UNPROFOR </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Jarcevic Welcomes Extension for UNPROFOR </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0104134294 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1258 GMT 1 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0104134294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 1 Apr (TANJUG) -- Slobodan Jarcevic, 
minister of foreign affairs of the republic of Serb Krajina 
[RSK], today welcomed the UN Security Council resolution 
extending the UNPROFOR [UN Protection Forces] mandate by six 
months. 
  Noting that due to financial difficulties the United Nations 
will send only 3,500 fresh soldiers, Jarcevic stressed in a 
statement for Radio Yugoslavia that the shortage of soldiers 
would be made up with the authority of the United States and 
Russia because "they guaranteed that peace along the border 
between the RSK and the Republic of Croatia would not be 
violated." 
  The RSK foreign minister also welcomed the fact that NATO 
will surveil the air space between the RSK and Croatia in order 
to "protect the blue helmets." 
  Jarcevic expressed the hope that the RSK will be 
internationally recognized in the next six months, that Zagreb 
will understand that it cannot defeat Krajina militarily, and 
that the Croatian demand to the United Nations to force the 
Serbs to return to Croatia with NATO's help cannot be fulfilled. 
  "In its actions, Croatia must take as the starting point the 
current state of affairs and the fact that Krajian exists," 
Jarcevic told Radio Yugoslavia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

