<F P=100> HUNGARY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Boross-Chernomyrdin News Conference on Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Boross-Chernomyrdin News Conference on Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0104144694 Budapest Kossuth Radio Network in Hungarian 
1400 GMT 1 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0104144694 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest Kossuth Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Hungarian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Istvan Kulcsar] </F>
  [Text] Hungarian Prime Minister Peter Boross and Russian 
Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin, along with the Hungarian and 
Russian ministers concerned, signed six documents early this 
afternoon in the Cupola Hall of the parliament building here in 
Budapest. 
  At their subsequent news conference, Peter Boross 
highlighted 
two agreements in particular: The first provides for the 
transportation to Russia of the spent heating elements of the 
Paks nuclear power station, and the second for the settling of 
the Russian debt. The modalities of the latter are to be 
services, deliveries of goods, and access for the Hungarian side 
to property in Russia in Russian or mixed enterprises. 
  The latter was warmly welcomed by Prime Minister 
Chernomyrdin, who stated that the trade the two countries 
conducted with each other last year could be doubled or even 
tripled in the medium term. 
  In answer to questions, the Russian prime minister said that 
his country welcomes Hungary's intention to join the European 
Union. As for Hungary's possibly joining NATO, that is 
something that will have to be decided by the Hungarian 
leadership and the Hungarian people. 
  Peter Boross stated that the Hungarian-Russian discussions 
have been even more successful than expected. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

