<H3> <TI>   Karabashev on Trip to Australia, Indonesia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Karabashev on Trip to Australia, Indonesia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0204185894 Sofia BTA in English 1705 GMT 2 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0204185894 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sofia, April 2 (BTA) -- The ten-day visit of Deputy 
Prime Minister Valentin Karabashev to Australia and Indonesia 
ended today. He was accompanied by representatives of 15 
Bulgarian companies. The delegation negotiated on cooperation 
in the extraction of mineral resources, in transport and trade. 
They had talks with high-ranking government officials and heads 
of leading companies, Mr. Karabashev told reporters. It is 
unnatural not to use trade diplomacy to achieve some results in 
coutries holding key positions is eastern Asia, he said. 
  The chairman of the Geology and Mineral Resources Committee, 
Mr. Antony Panayotov, discussed the introduction of new 
technologies in gold and copper ore mining. He familiarized 
Australian companies with the possibilities to participate in 
auctions of oil prospecting blocks in the Black Sea shelf. 
Australian businessmen were interested in possible cooperation 
in the sphere of transport and in leasing planes of the Balkan 
air carrier. 
  This year the largest quantities of imported raw sugar are 
likely to come from Australia, said Mr. Valentin Karabashev. 
  Draft agreements on the avoidance of double taxation and 
mutual protection of investments were presented to the 
Australian government three months ago. According to the deputy 
prime minister, they will be signed in the near future. An 
agreement on the avoidance of double taxation has already been 
signed with Indonesia, now another step will be made towards 
free trade between the two countries. Interest towards the 
Bulgarian delegation was unexpectedly lively. "We might 
possibly start importing rubber directly from Indonesia, without 
the mediation of Singaporean companies," Mr. Karabashev pointed 
out. 

</TEXT>

