<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Bulgaria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Council of Europe Delegation Visits </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Council of Europe Delegation Visits </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0104185294 Sofia BTA in English 1747 GMT 1 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0104185294 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sofia, April 1 (BTA) -- Mr. Friedrich Koenig, 
rapporteur of the Political Committee of the Council of Europe's 
Parliamentary Assembly, and Mr. Dominique Columberg, rapporteur 
of the Legal Committee of the Parliamentary Assembly, have been 
on a visit to this country since March 30. 
  Mr. Koenig and Mr. Columberg are here in connection with the 
Parliamentary Assembly's decision to check on the compliance of 
newly-admitted member countries with membership requirements and 
to draft a resolution on the current political situation in this 
country. In parliament they met with Bulgaria's permanent 
delegation to the Parliamentary Assembly, as well as with 
representatives of the five parliamentary groups. Each of them 
set forth its views on the current political situation, the 
government's economic and financial policy, the human rights of 
minorities, parliament's law-making and the difficulties faced 
by this country during the transition period. 
  Today Mr. Koenig and Mr. Columberg met with National 
Assembly 
Chairman Aleksandur Yordanov. He stressed that the political 
forces are in agreement on the principles and priorities of 
Bulgaria's foreign policy. He pointed out that the reforms have 
slowed down, stressing that they must continue. 
  Acting Prime Minister Evgeni Matinchev and Justice Minister 
Petur Kornazhev today met with Mr. Koenig and Mr. Columberg. 
The government press office said the guests had been 
familiarized in detail with the government's activity, as well 
as with the formidable difficulties it has to deal with. Asked 
about the so- called re-communization, Mr. Matinchev and Mr. 
Kornazhev spoke at length, presenting solid arguments. The 
guests showed a special interest in executive-judiciary 
relations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

