<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Havel Stresses Need To Respect Constitution </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Havel Stresses Need To Respect Constitution </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0304151594 Prague CTK in English 1436 GMT 3 Apr 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0304151594 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague, April 3 (CTK) -- Czech President Vaclav 
Havel said today he had never favoured much a bicameral 
parliamentary system, but stressed that the Constitution had to 
be respected and therefore the Senate should be elected this 
year. 
  Speaking in his regular Sunday radio programme "Talks from 
Lany", Havel said that if the parliamentarians reached the 
agreement that the Cezch Republic should have a unicameral 
parliamentary system, this would require not only "the deletion 
of several articles from the Constitution, but the rewriting of 
the whole Constitution." The way of filling the second chamber 
of the parliament, Senate, is currently the object of a broad 
and often heated discussion in the government coalition. 
  The strongest coalition party, the Civic Democratic Party 
(ODS) of Premier Vaclav Klaus has insisted on the elections to 
be held in 81 one-mandate constituencies. In the first 
elections the constituencies would be divided into three groups: 
In the first senators would be elected for two years, in the 
second for four years and in the third for six years. Under the 
Constitution the senators are to be elected for six-year terms 
with one third of them being replaced every two years. 
  The three other coalition parties have proposed 27 
constituencies each of which would have three mandates in the 
first elections and one mandate in the following balloting. The 
elections would probably be held in the autumn along with local 
elections. Elections to the existing Chamber of Deputies are 
scheduled to be held in 1996. The deputies are elected for 
four-year terms. 
  Havel welcomed the compromise solution proposed by deputies 
at the end of March. Under it three senators would be elected 
in 27 "large constituencies." Each of them would comprise three 
smaller ones which would make a total of 81 as proposed by the 
ODS. Havel said this would not breach the Constitution. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-7662 </DOCNO>
