<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Romania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Iliescu Returns From Greece, Summarizes Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Iliescu Returns From Greece, Summarizes Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0104142994 Bucharest ROMPRES in English 0941 GMT 1 Apr 94 
-- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0104142994 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest ROMPRES </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bucharest ROMPRES, 1/4/1994 -- Romania's President 
Ion Iliescu returned Thursday evening [31 March] to Bucharest 
after a two-day formal visit to Greece at the invitation of the 
Greek president. On his arrival in Bucharest President Iliescu 
stated among other things: 
  "We had a very busy schedule with interviews with President 
Konstandinos Karamanlis, with Premier Andreas Papandreou, with 
several members of the government and of parliamentary parties, 
as well as with representatives of business and banking circles. 
The common note of these interviews was their warm atmosphere. 
On one side we assessed the good level of the ties between our 
countries and a considerable similarity of opinions as regards 
issues of our direct concern, as well as international 
developments in our area and in Europe at large. We have also 
noticed the firm political will on both sides to support the 
expansion, diversification, and development of ties in all 
fields, especially the economic ones, and we also considered the 
current volume of commercial exchanges as modest compared to the 
potential of our economies. From this point of view my opinion 
is that there is a real interest and a climate of confidence 
among business and economic circles of both countries to expand 
these relations. However, these issues will be debated on the 
forthcoming session of the joint commission due next week in 
Athens. Worth mentioning would be also a new and positive 
element in our relations in the banking system." 
  "As for the issues confronting our area and Europe in 
general, we also noticed a similarity of opinions in their 
approach. Referring to Yugoslavia, both sides were of the 
opinion that progress could be made only by supporting efforts 
for a political approach of the potential solutions to be found, 
and that steps made until present in this direction are 
sufficiently promising." 
  Romania's president was accompanied during his visit to 
Greece by Foreign Minister Teodor Melescanu, by Traian Chebeleu, 
presidential aide, and by other officials. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

