<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry To Set Up `Fast Deployment Brigade' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ministry To Set Up `Fast Deployment Brigade' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0504113394 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 1000 
GMT 5 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0504113394 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Czech </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Czech Defense Ministry has decided to form its 
own fast deployment unit. Our correspondent Milan Repka reports: 
  Defense Minister Antonin Baudys has said that a fast 
deployment brigade will deal with, above all, the solution of 
sudden crisis situations at any place in the Czech Republic, 
including situations where the state is under threat. 
  According to Baudys, this unit should have about 3,000 men 
and should represent some kind of model of the future Czech 
Army. The equipment of this brigade should be compatible with 
the equipment of NATO countries, both in the case of hand 
weapons and helicopters. 
  As Baudys went on to say, he and Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus 
agreed on putting domestic arms production first, while taking 
its quality strictly into account. 
  Another step of the ministry within the framework of 
transformation of the Czech Army is the necessary reduction of a 
large number of commander posts. In this connection, Baudys 
designated the basic principle of this transformation--above 
all, orientation toward recruiting new officers to achieve the 
aim of the Army service having to become attractive for high 
quality people. 

</TEXT>

