<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Skeptical of Partnership for Peace </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official Skeptical of Partnership for Peace </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0504114894 Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network in Polish 1005 
GMT 5 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0504114894 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network </F>
<F P=105>  Polish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] [Announcer] Poland has no chance to join NATO in the 
near future. This is an opinion expressed by Longin Pastusiak, 
deputy chairman of the Sejm Foreign Affairs Commission, who 
returned from Washington a few days ago. According to the 
professor, the Partnership for Peace program can be treated as 
the last stop before NATO. 
  [Begin Pastusiak recording] The program does not provide 
guarantees of security for us. Consequently, Article 5, the key 
article of the North Atlantic Treaty, which declares that 
aggression against a NATO member state means aggression against 
the entire NATO organization, will not apply to Poland. 
However, the states that will be included in the Partnership 
for Peace program will be covered by Article 4, which envisages 
that, in a situation of conflict or when Poland's security is 
threatened, the NATO countries would hold a meeting and carry 
out consultations. Such consultations might lead to military 
action, but it is not said clearly. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

