<H3> <TI>   `Disquiet' Over Agreement With Serbs </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Disquiet' Over Agreement With Serbs </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0404193694 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1900 GMT 4 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0404193694 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report from Zagreb by Nada al-Isa] </F>
  [Text] The Croat-Serb agreement is still causing disquiet. 
The Croatian opposition is still not clear about the conditions 
under which it was signed or what has happened to the maps -- 
there were 35 on the table. There have been no offical 
statements on this from the Croatian side. They are keeping 
things concealed as best they can. 
  However the Zagreb press has published a map reprinted from 
the Vienna-based paper DER STANDARD and the borders on the map 
are shown in such a way as to give any Croat a headache. For 
example, the so-called republic of Serb Krajina has outlets to 
the sea at Biograd and Zadar, but what tops it all, the papers 
say, is that even Osijek is in the so-called Krajina. Is the 
leadership really concealing such a thing from ordinary people? 
  President Tudjman also has different political problems 
every 
day. The replaced Josip Manolic has announced that he is off to 
Washington as early as today where he is to have talks with U.S. 
congressmen responsible for military issues. The meeting has 
allegedly been fixed up by Dobroslav Paraga. So Manolic is not 
travelling to Washington with Tudjman's blessing. Who is he 
representing? What is behind the visit? Those in the know say 
that Dr Tudjman himself would like to know the answer to this 
question. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

