<H3> <TI>   Government Protests Croatian Decision on Refugees </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Protests Croatian Decision on Refugees </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0404153994 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1300 GMT 4 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0404153994 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Bosnia-Herzegovina Government has written to the 
Government of the Republic of Croatia from today's session 
[words indistinct]. 
  We were surprised to hear the instructions of the Croatian 
Government's Office for Refugees, which discontinues refugee 
status in the Republic of Croatia for citizens from the area of 
the Mostar municipality. Our surprise is all the greater since 
we know that Arif Smajkic, minister for refugees, labor, and 
social policy in the Bosnia-Herzegovina Government, during his 
recent visit and talks with deputy prime minister of the 
Croatian Government Ivica Kostovic, and director of the Office 
for Refugees Adalbert Rebic agreed on joint activities of the 
two governments regarding the return of refugees from Croatia to 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. An identical agreement was reached with the 
representatives of the Croatian people in Bosnia-Herzegovina at 
the recently held Constituent Assembly of the Bosnia-Herzegovina 
Federation. Therefore, we propose to the Croatian Government to 
annul the aforementioned instructions and create conditions for 
joint preparations for all activities pertaining to the 
organized return of refugees and displaced persons to which we 
are obliged by the provisions of international treaties on the 
repatriation of refugees, reads the statement of the Information 
Ministry. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

