<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs Deny `Ethnic Cleansing' in Prijedor </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Serbs Deny `Ethnic Cleansing' in Prijedor </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0304170594 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1623 GMT 3 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0304170594 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Banja Luka, 3 Apr (TANJUG) -- The murders which took 
place in Prijedor between 29 March and 1 April are criminal acts 
commited by hitherto unidentified perpetrators, and intensive 
action is being taken to uncover those who committed them, the 
interior ministry of the Srpska republic [RS] has said in a 
statement. 
  The statement says that eight criminal acts of murder were 
committed in the specified period and that 16 people, mainly 
Muslims, lost their lives [as received]. 
  Regarding claims by some foreign agencies that the murders 
were part of ethnic cleansing in and around Prijedor, the 
statement says that these were criminal acts by hitherto 
unidentified perpetrators, against whom criminal charges have 
been filed. 
  "Teams of Ministry of Internal Affairs and security organs 
of 
the Srpska republic army are working intensively on collecting 
data in order to identify and arrest the perpetrators of the 
crimes," the statement says and adds that all possible 
preventive measures are being taken to stop any further 
escalation of crime. 
  The interior ministry points to the fact that the events in 
Prijedor took place during the Muslim spring offensive, which -- 
through the crimes committed -- demonstrated that the Muslims 
were prepared to use all available means to achieve their goals. 
This contributed to the escalation of the interethnic conflicts 
in this area, where such conflicts had not occurred for a long 
time. 
  The RS interior ministry appeals to all international 
institutions "which have influence in the area" to use it to 
protect the Serb population in the areas controlled by Muslims. 
  They particularly demand that prisoners be treated according 
to international law. 
  In this way extremists among the Serb people can also be 
opposed more effectively and better protection can be given to 
the Serb people and all citizens living on the RS territory, the 
statement says in conclusion. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-7717 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu065_i_94016" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-065 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  3 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karadzic Order on Investigation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Karadzic Order on Investigation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0304154094 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1411 GMT 3 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0304154094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 3 Apr (TANJUG) -- Radovan Karadzic, 
president of the Srpska republic, today issued a strict order to 
relevant organs to speed up the investigation in Prijedor to 
uncover the perpetrators of the criminal activities and to 
arrest all those responsible for the events in the town, the 
Srpska republic president's office said in a statement. 
  The statement, forwarded to TANJUG, says that Radovan 
Karadzic's order particularly stressed that enemies of the 
Srpska republic were intensifying attacks against the 
sovereignty and independence of the Srpska republic, in an 
attempt to create a state of chaos, to compromise its civilian 
authorities, and prevent the creation and functioning of the 
Serb state. 
  The Srpska republic president also issued strict 
instructions 
regarding the safeguarding of the security of members of 
minorities, as well as instructions to all Srpska republic 
civilian and military authorities to give all possible help to 
the International Red Cross, the statement says. 
  President Karadzic's order also emphasized that all 
perpetrators of criminal activities were to be tried and most 
severely punished before the entire world public, the statement 
says in conclusion. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

