Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Red Cross Postpones Evacuation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Red Cross Postpones Evacuation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0404203894 Paris AFP in English 2026 GMT 4 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0404203894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, April 4 (AFP) -- The Red Cross Monday [4 
April] postponed plans to evacuate thousands of Moslems from the 
town of Prijedor following ethnic killings, citing disagreement 
with Bosnian Serbs over how many people are to leave. 
  The announcement came from Andreas Kuhn of the International 
Committee of the Red Cross after a meeting with Bosnian Serb 
leader Radovan Karadzic in the Bosnian Serb stronghold of Pale 
near Sarajevo. 
  "I am not sure whether we will go back to negotiation or 
we'll take other measures" to protect the Moslems of Prijedor in 
western Bosnia, Kuhn said. "This is to be decided in Geneva." 
  Asked if the Red Cross continued with preparations for the 
evacuation, Kuhn said, "We are ready and we remain ready." 
  The Red Cross and the United Nations had planned to begin 
the 
evacuation of about 6,000 people from Prijedor on Tuesday. 
  Moslems there fear for their lives following a massacre last 
week in which 17 Moslems and three Croats were killed, UN 
officials say. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-7720 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu065_i_94019" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-065 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   ICRC Says Situation `Better' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ICRC Says Situation `Better' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0404164694 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1538 GMT 4 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0404164694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Banja Luka, 4 Mar (TANJUG) -- Christian Bruner, an 
International Committee of the Red Cross [ICRC] official in 
Banja Luka, has told a TANJUG correspondent that there will be 
no large-scale evacuation of the Muslim and Croat population 
tomorrow as intimated by some of the world's media, including 
the Croatian and Muslim media. 
  Bruner says the situation in Prijedor is much better 
following the order of Radovan Karadzic, president of the Srpska 
republic, that an investigation into the killings in Prijedor be 
completed so that those responsible are discovered. 
  Bruner says that it is only possible for permission to be 
granted for the resettlement of a number of people who have 
expressed great fear for their lives and who want to leave 
Prijedor. This resettlement will not begin tomorrow either but 
will be carried out over the next few days. 
  He stresses that security guarantees from the Serb 
authorities are needed during their transportation for this 
resettlement to take place. He added that talks will begin 
tomorrow between ICRC representatives and the Srpska republic 
authorities and that he believes that all the necessary 
gaurantees will be given. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

