<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Muslims Shelling Croat Areas of Mostar </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Muslims Shelling Croat Areas of Mostar </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0404235394 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2249 GMT 4 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0404235394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Belgrade, April 4 (TANJUG) - A Croatian radio 
correspondent reported from Mostar on Monday evening that the 
ceasefire has been seriously violated in this town in southern 
Bosnia-Herzegovina after several heavy shells were fired from 
Moslem east Mostar on Croat west Mostar. 
  Radio Free Europe reported this evening that two Moslem 
soldiers were killed and four were wounded in Croat-Moslem 
clashes near Gornji Vakuf. 
  Moslem Radio Sarajevo has not reported about Moslem-Croat 
clashes around Gornji Vakuf these days, but Croatian radio 
claims that the fighting is between two groups of smugglers. 
The Croatian radio did not say which side sustained casualties. 
  Military sources of the Croatian Defence Council (HVO) have 
said that the HVO military police will try to seize the 
smugglers, who are said to have "abused the reached agreements 
on opening communications and are not refraining even from armed 
clashes." 
  Bosnian Croats and Moslems signed an agreement on the 
forming 
of a Moslem-Croat federation in Washington in mid-March under 
strong pressure from the United States. The federation 
Constitution has already been adopted but clashes between the 
two peoples continue. Serbs, the third nation who live in this 
former Yugoslav republic were not invited to the Washington 
talks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

