<F P=100> ROMANIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbian President, Jovanovic Arrive for Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Serbian President, Jovanovic Arrive for Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Melescanu Meets With Jovanovic </H4>

<F P=102> AU0504132994 Paris AFP in English 1256 GMT 5 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0504132994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bucharest, April 5 (AFP) -- Romanian Foreign 
Minister Teodor Melescanu said Tuesday that he hoped Serbia 
would make an effort in peace negotiations on Bosnia and in turn 
be rewarded with lighter sanctions. President Slobodan 
Milosevic and Foreign Affairs Minister Vladislav Jovanovic of 
Serbia were on an official visit to Romania Tuesday. 
  In an interview with AFP, Melescanu said: "The Serbs can not 
and must not stay outside of the peace process." He referred to 
the recent accord forming a Moslem-Croat federation in Bosnia 
which the Serbs refused to join. 
  He said that if the Serbs agreed to form some kind of 
relationship with the new federation, sanctions imposed on rump 
Yugoslavia should be eased. "The goal of the embargo is not to 
create useless suffering but to encourage a peaceful solution to 
the conflict," he said. "One must use the carrot as well as the 
stick." 
  He said Bucharest has a direct interest in a peaceful end to 
the conflict. Romania has lost nearly seven billion dollars in 
trade since the sanctions against Serbia and Montenegro began 
two years ago. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

