<F P=100> ROMANIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbian President, Jovanovic Arrive for Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Serbian President, Jovanovic Arrive for Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Milosevic: Sanctions `No Longer Justified' </H4>

<F P=102> AU0504152594 Bucharest Radio Romania Network in Romanian 
1300 GMT 5 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0504152594 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest Radio Romania Network </F>
<F P=105>  Romanian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Today, at Villa Lac-2, Serbian President Slobodan 
Milosevic held talks with Romanian Prime Minister Nicolae 
Vacaroiu. The talks were attended by the ambassador of the 
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia [FRY] to Bucharest. 
  A press release that was faxed to us a short while ago says 
that during their talks President Slobodan Milosevic -- after 
outlining the high level reached in bilateral relations before 
the introduction of economic sanctions against the FRY -- 
expressed his conviction that those sanctions will soon be 
lifted because, considering the recent evolution of the 
political situation in that area, they are no longer justified. 
Anticipating that moment, impatiently looked forward to not only 
by Serbia but also by its neighbors, who are severely affected 
by the embargo imposed by the international community, it is 
necessary that ways of cultural, scientific, and educational 
cooperation should be examined now, whereas after the partial or 
total lifting of the sanctions cooperation between Serbia and 
Romania should also be extended to industry, investments, 
finance, and commerce, so that within a short time the level of 
bilateral exchanges should equal or surpass the previous levels, 
the guest stressed. 
  In turn, Vacaroiu pointed out that Romania has strictly 
observed the international embargo imposed on the FRY but it 
also consequently acted by intervening at international fora for 
the reduction of the level of those sanctions, especially 
considering recent political evolutions that give reason to hope 
for the peaceful settlement of the conflicts that broke out out 
with the dismembering of the former Yugoslav Federation. The 
consequences of the embargo were drastic for Romania as well, 
especially because they came in addition to the difficulties 
emerged in the process of economic reform and industrial 
restructuring currently under way in our country. A number of 
enterprises, the Romanian prime minister emphasized, which used 
to work in cooperation with Serbian firms had to suspend their 
activity, which accentuated the decline of our industrial 
production and amplified unemployment. 
  During their meeting, the parties agreed to examine, at the 
level of a joint commission, possibilities of resuming, as soon 
as possible, bilateral economic and commercial relations, once 
the level of the international sanctions imposed on the FRY is 
diminished or the sanctions are totally lifted. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-7748 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu066_r_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-066 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  5 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ROMANIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbian President, Jovanovic Arrive for Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Serbian President, Jovanovic Arrive for Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Milosevic on `Excellent' Relations </H4>

<F P=102> AU0504183594 Belgrade Radio Beograd Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1700 GMT 5 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0504183594 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade Radio Beograd Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Statement by Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic at a news </F>
conference in Bucharest on 5 April -- recorded] 
  [Text] In brief, our mutual relations could be described 
as very good, I would even say excellent, but we still expect 
them to continually and constantly improve. There are many 
mutual interests, as well as numerous reasons for that. A few 
minutes ago President Iliescu mentioned some figures. These are 
our joint modest estimates of the possibilities for developing 
our cooperation. This is why it is absurd that presently we 
cannot realize much of that and improve the standard of living 
and our economies, because of the administrative measures and 
sanctions that represent an anachronism at the end of the 20th 
century, and which were unfortunately imposed by the countries 
that consider themselves to be more cultured and more civilized. 
  However, I am convinced that life itself will bring down 
such 
an approach, which is not civilized and which runs counter to 
the basic laws of the modern world that is integrating and 
uniting itself, the world that is permeating itself. In other 
words, the world that is opposite to these processes will have 
to go where it belongs, into the inglorious past, and I hope, 
will do so very quickly. 
  In any case, I am sure that regarding our country and 
friendly Romania, both sides will maximally contribute to this. 
There is no doubt, and this is something we jointly concluded 
today, that good mutual relations between our two countries 
represent an important factor of stability in this region. We 
rate our mutual cooperation very highly. We rate very highly 
the objective approach by Romania and President Iliescu to the 
problems of the Yugoslav crisis and believe that there is every 
reason for our cooperation in future to only improve and 
increase in the interest of both peoples and both countries. 
  We are very satisfied with everything we heard and saw and 
we 
are convinced in the success of our mutual cooperation. 

</TEXT>

