<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Walesa, Pawlak, Finnish Foreign Minister Meet </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Walesa, Pawlak, Finnish Foreign Minister Meet </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0604111994 Warsaw PAP in Polish 1050 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0604111994 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>
<F P=105>  Polish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, 6 Apr--President Lech Walesa, while 
receiving Heikki Haavisto, Finland's foreign minister, in the 
Belweder on 6 April, expressed Poland's will to expand contacts 
with Finland. Earlier, Minister Haavisto was received by Prime 
Minister Waldemar Pawlak. 
  According to the Polish president, Polish-Finnish relations 
are "not bad," but they do not make full use of all of the 
capabilities of either of the two countries. In his opinion, 
Poland and Finland, as medium-size countries, could play a 
greater role in international organizations. Lech Walesa said 
that Poland and Finland want to join European organizations that 
"have proved themselves so far." Finland has already succeeded 
in this field. Poland still has a long way to go, the president 
said. 
  The subject of talks with Waldemar Pawlak was economic 
cooperation between the two states and trade exchange. The 
prime minister conveyed to the Finnish minister an invitation 
for the head of the Finnish Government to pay a visit to Poland. 

</TEXT>

