<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Crisis of Authority' Among Serb Leaders Viewed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Crisis of Authority' Among Serb Leaders Viewed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0504133894 Paris AFP in English 1338 GMT 5 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0504133894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Maurice Lubatti] </F>
  [Text] Geneva, April 5 (AFP) -- Apparent swings in policy 
regarding the enclave of Gorazde and the non-Serb population in 
the Banja Luka region suggest there could be a crisis of 
authority among the separatist Bosnian Serbs, diplomats at the 
Conference on Yugoslavia said here Tuesday. 
  "Just when there appeared to be a process of normalisation 
under way, with some spirit of reconciliation among the Bosnian 
Serb authorities, everything has been thrown into question with 
this upsurge in tension," a negotiator here said on condition of 
anonymity. 
  A week-long Serb onslaught on the eastern Bosnian enclave of 
Gorazde, and a last-minute reversal on the proposed evacuation 
of several thousand non-Serbs from the northern town of Prijedor 
following a massacre last week, have thrown the spotlight onto 
possible divergences among the Serb leadership. 
  Differences have long been known to exist between separatist 
hardliners, mainly in the army and in the Serbs' Banja Luka 
stronghold, and supporters of Radovan Karadzic, leader of the 
self-proclaimed Serb Republic based at Pale, just outside 
Sarajevo. 
  These differences are seen as the most likely cause of the 
latest developments, the most astonishing of which was 
Karadzic's volte- face over the evacuation of up to 6,000 
Moslems and Croats from Prijedor, scheduled to take place on 
Tuesday. 
  On Sunday Karadzic gave written orders authorising UN and 
Red 
Cross officials to proceed with the evacuation, demanded by the 
non-Serb population of the region which had been terrorised by 
Serb militants. 
  Then on Monday he vetoed the agreed figure of 6,000, saying 
that such a large-scale evacuation was unncessary since, he 
said, measures had been taken to protect civilians in Prijedor. 
The operation was postponed as a result of the reversal. 
  The fighting in the Gorazde region comes after a ceasefire 
was agreed between Bosnians and Serbs in Sarajevo. 
  Rivalry between Serb civilian and military authorities is 
also seen as the likely explanation for such incidents as the 
theft of parcels at Banja Luka, or the confiscation of food 
supplies destined for the northern enclave of Maglaj. 
  The commander of Bosnian Serb forces, General Ratko Mladic, 
seen as the most militant of hardliners, currently spends the 
bulk of his time in the Banja Luka sector rather than at Pale, 
diplomats noted. 
  Unconfirmed reports here indicate that Mladic has fallen out 
with Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic, Karadzic's sponsor in 
the Bosnian conflict. 
  European Union negotiator Lord Owen said last week that at 
his last meeting with Milosevic he had found the Serbian leader 
more amenable to a negotiated settlement to the conflict. 
Serbia has been severely hit by economic sanctions imposed on 
Belgrade in May 1992. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-7772 </DOCNO>
