<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serbs, UN Officials Agree on Humanitarian Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Serbs, UN Officials Agree on Humanitarian Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0504202094 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1933 GMT 5 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0504202094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, 5 Apr (TANJUG) -- Nikola Koljevic, vice 
president of the Srpska republic, had a meeting in Pale this 
afternoon with the UN secretary general's envoy (Sergio de Melo) 
and with Andreas Kuhn, delegate of the International Committee 
of the Red Cross [ICRC]. 
  The talks that took place on this occasion referred to the 
situation in Prijedor and Gorazde and to ways of improving the 
humanitarian situation in former Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  We agreed to make it possible for the people who wish to 
leave the territory of the Srpska republic to do so. We will 
provide the necessary security measures and guarantees. Those 
who wish to stay will be protected by the Serb authorities, 
Koljevic said after the talks. 
  Koljevic also said that the representatives of the 
international organizations were told that the Serb authorities 
insist on the Serbs in Sarajevo, Tuzla, and central Bosnia being 
given the same treatment, including the right to leave 
Muslim-controlled territory, if they so wish. 
  He added that the Srpska republic's authorities will discuss 
all possibilities for giving ICRC representatives access to 
Gorazde as soon as possible. 
  The UN secretary general's envoy said that "this is not a 
time for dangerous military activities" and that "the most 
important thing is the protection of the Gorazde area." 
  The ICRC representative said the agreement that was reached 
will "satisfy both sides and will provide the answer to the 
question of how to solve the situation in Prijedor." 
  He also said that a number of "specific measures for 
improving the humanitarian situation in Gorazde" have been 
agreed and that the ICRC intends to send food and medicine there 
as soon as possible. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

