<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN on Gorazde, Prijedor </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN on Gorazde, Prijedor </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0504140194 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1332 GMT 5 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0504140194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Geneva, April 5 (TANJUG) -- A spokesman for the U.N. 
High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), Ron Redmond, said on 
Tuesday that the situation in the regions of Banja Luka and 
Prijedor (northern Bosnia-Herzegovina) has stabilized since last 
week but that UNHCR was concerned about the fierceness of 
fighting around Gorazde (eastern Bosnia-Herzegovina). 
  The tragic events in Prijedor (northwest Bosnian Serb 
Republic) which killed 16 civilians, mostly Moslems, between 
March 29 and April 1, broke out after the Moslem army delivered 
six massacred Serb bodies to the Prijedor authorities. 
  The representatives of the local authorities and the ruling 
Serb Democratic Party (SDS) strongly condemned these murders on 
Tuesday. The enquiry conducted so far showed that many persons 
had participated in the killings and that they were committed 
for gain, while the Prijedor police underscored that they would 
persist with solving of each particular case. 
  Redmond set out that UNHCR was concerned about the 
development of the situation in Gorazde where heavy fighting was 
going on, and said that according to the latest U.N. report 
from Gorazde no UNHCR convoy had been allowed to enter the town 
since March 22. 
  U.N. Security Council President Colin Keating said on Monday 
that UNPROFOR [UN Protection Forces] statements showed that the 
Moslems had provoked the latest fighting with Serbs in Gorazde. 
  The heavy Moslem offensive on Serb positions and villages 
was 
launched from Gorazde in late March, although the town should 
have been demilitarized as a U.N. protected area last spring. 
Over 10,000 Moslem troops are engaged in the operations. 
  After signing the Washington Agreement to form a 
Moslem-Croat 
Federation in Bosnia-Herzegovina in March, the Moslems launched 
an all-out offensive on the Bosnian Serb Republic in an attempt 
to gain as much territory as possible before the resumption of 
the peace talks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-7781 </DOCNO>
