<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN on Death Toll </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN on Death Toll </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0504203894 Paris AFP in English 2024 GMT 5 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0504203894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, April 5 (AFP) -- Hundreds of refugees 
poured into Gorazde from neighbouring villages Tuesday as Serb 
forces pressed on with an offensive against the Moslem enclave 
in eastern Bosnia, the United Nations said. 
  According to UN High Commissioner for Refugees [UNHCR] 
spokesman Kris Janowski, 52 people have died and 249 had been 
wounded in the week-old offensive. 
  Radio Sarajevo put the toll even higher: at least 73 dead 
and over 300 injured. 
  Witnesses reported eight villages destroyed by Serb 
artillery 
in the southern part of the enclave, leaving some 1,500 people 
wandering around looking for shelter, the UN refugee agency said. 
  Major Rob Annink, a spokesman for the UN Protection Force 
[UNPROFOR] in Sarajevo, said Serb forces had penetrated eight to 
10 kilometers (five to six miles) into the southern part of the 
enclave and were continuing their attacks on the northeast and 
southeast sectors. 
  There were conflicting reports on how far the Serbs were 
from 
Gorazde itself. Annink said they were 10 kilometers (six miles) 
away, but one military source speaking on condition of anonymity 
put them at just over three kilometers (two miles) from the 
southern suburbs of the town. 
  Bosnian President Alija Izetbegovic spoke by telephone with 
the U.S. Secretary of State Warren Cristopher about the 
situation in Gorazde as well as with President Clinton's special 
envoy Charles Redman and UN special envoy Yasushi Akashi. 
  At the end of a special meeting, the Bosnian Presidency 
issued a statement informing the Bosnian Army and population 
that "they have to be ready for all contingencies." 
  "The situation in Gorazde and Bihac (another besieged Moslem 
enclave, in northwestern Bosnia) as well as the ethnic cleansing 
are proof that, unfortunately, the war is not over," the 
statement said. 
  The fighting in Gorazde and Bihac comes as ceasefires are 
generally holding in Sarajevo and central Bosnia. 
  Around 300 people marched in Sarajevo Tuesday to protest 
what 
they called the international community's indifference to Serb 
aggression. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

