<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Krajina Officials Criticize U.S. Newspaper </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Krajina Officials Criticize U.S. Newspaper </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0604124194 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1153 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0604124194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, April 6 (TANJUG) -- Officials of the 
Republic of Serb Krajina (RSK) have termed "sheer media ploy and 
distortion" the manner in which THE WASHINGTON POST has 
interpreted their statements. 
  RSK Foreign Minister Slobodan Jarcevic and Parliamentary 
Foreign Policy Committee Chairman Lazar Macura have said that 
their statements made to WASHINGTON POST's journalist John 
Pomfrit were "rephrased to suit the Croatian or possibly 
American view of things," and that "vital parts were omitted, 
ones which reflect the realistic positions of Serb politicians," 
the RSK news agency ISKRA said on Tuesday. 
  The U.S. daily said in an article in connection with the 
effectuation of the agreement on the cessation of hostilities 
between the RSK and Croatia on April 4 that the RSK was showing 
growing readiness, in exchange for broad autonomy, to agree to 
live together with Croats and be under Zagreb's sovereignty. 
  However, the RSK maintains that the ceasefire agreement in 
no 
way prejudices a political solution to the problem. 
  ISKRA quoted Jarcevic as saying that he had stated to THE 
WASHINGTON POST journalist that he would resign his post in the 
RSK government if the incredible was to happen and the Serb 
state was to agree to negotiate on autonomy, a federation or 
confederation with Croatia. THE WASHINGTON POST, however, 
interpreted Jarcevic as allegedly saying that he would be the 
first to return to Belgrade if the RSK was to lose its 
independence. 
  Macura, who stated that Krajina could be part of Croatia 
only 
if the big powers were to make Croatia be part of a new 
Yugoslavia and if Krajina was to have political autonomy in the 
new state, was interpreted in THE WASHINGTON POST as allegedly 
saying that the Krajina Serbs could live as citizens of Croatia 
if Croatia was to guarantee them equal rights. 
  The RSK was proclaimed in 1991 in response to Croatia's 
forcible secession from the then Yugoslav Federation and the 
attempts of Croatian authorities to deny the Serbs the status of 
a constituent people and reduce them to a national minority. 
  In mid-March this year, after three years of war and 
Croatia's four attempts to impose its authority in the RSK by 
means of force, the two sides signed an agreement on the 
cessation of hostilities. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-7788 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu066_m_94001" </HT>


