<F P=100> THE FORMER YUGOSLAV REPUBLIC OF MACEDONIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gligorov on `Partnership,' U.S. Interests </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Gligorov on `Partnership,' U.S. Interests </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0504161294 Skopje MILS-NEWS in English 5 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0504161294 </F>
<F P=104>  Skopje MILS-NEWS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Neither Military Bases Nor Accession"] </F>
  [Text] "Macedonia [The Former Yugoslav Republic of 
Macedonia -- FYROM] wishes to join the program `Partnership for 
Peace,' since under the conditions of historical passion and 
grand appetites that have been ruling the Balkans, and Macedonia 
being a small country, it sees its security in this NATO 
program," said President Gligorov in his interview for Belgrade 
weekly EKONOMSKA POLITIKA. In his interview, Mr. Gligorov speaks 
extensively also of the Greek embargo, pointing out that its aim 
is for Macedonia to accept the conditions given by Athens, which 
leads to identity loss of a nation and to destabilization of the 
region. He rejects the thesis that the Americans want Macedonian 
military bases to be given up to them in compensation for $1 
million. He also decidedly rejects the thesis that Washington 
requests Macedonia to join any of the state creation that are 
being formed on the territory of former Yugoslavia. 

</TEXT>

