<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serb Leader Deplores Prijedor Incidents </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Serb Leader Deplores Prijedor Incidents </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0504154894 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1435 GMT 5 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0504154894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, 5 Apr (TANJUG) -- Vladimir Lukic, prime 
minister of the Srpska republic, told TANJUG today that the 
authorities of the Srpska republic have taken all measures to 
bring to justice the perpetrators of the deplorable events in 
Prijedor as soon as possible. 
  "Some international humanitarian organizations were in a 
rush 
to make the Prijedor events into a spectacle, with the clear 
intention of accusing the authorities of the Srpska republic of 
attempting to carry out a systematic eviction of the Muslim 
population," Lukic said. He added that although there have been 
some excesses, the civilian and military authorities of the 
Srpska republic have been doing everything to minimize their 
number. 
  "It is regrettable that the international humanitarian 
organizations do not see the real state of affairs on the 
territory of former Bosnia-Herzegovina. It is a fact that the 
human rights of Serbs living in Muslim and Croat territories are 
under much greater threat," Lukic said, citing as an example the 
position of the Serbs in Sarajevo, Konjic, Zenica, and Tuzla. 
  He stated that the best confirmation of the situation 
regarding human rights and the rights of national minorities is 
the fact that many Muslims do not wish to leave the territory of 
the Srpska republic, because they feel completely safe and 
protected. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

